Promote O3 "ROB empty after substantial workload progress" from panic to clean exit.

The Round-5+ Milestone-E runs on pinned XS-GEM5 reach
"**** REAL SIMULATION ****", successfully commit the
benchmark's architectural workload (including the
final sentinel store + ebreak), and then reach the
halt-loop (`wfi / j halt`) at the tail of `bench.S`.
Within 40 000 cycles the stall monitor in
`src/cpu/o3/commit.cc::stuckCheckEvent` fires.

The already-landed `xs-gem5-commit-drain-exit.patch`
adds an `isCpuDrained()` escape hatch, but in practice
`isCpuDrained()` returns `false` on representative
benchmarks (`mem-stream`, `pointer-chase`, `alu`)
because the front-end continues fetching the
`halt: wfi / j halt` loop indefinitely, so fetch +
decode + rename never quiesce even after the
architectural workload has completed.

The stuck-check has three concrete invariants
available that together identify the workload-
finished case unambiguously:

  1. `lastCommitCycle > 0` — at least one
     architectural insn has already committed, so we
     are post-boot (not a genuine "fetch stuck before
     any commit" livelock where nothing ever
     retired).
  2. `rob->isEmpty(0)` — nothing in-flight, so we
     are not stuck on an uncommittable head (a
     genuine in-flight livelock would keep the ROB
     populated).
  3. `lastCommitedSeqNum[0] >= kMinCommitsForExit`
     (Round-11 tightening; value 1000) — at least
     1000 committed sequence numbers have retired.
     Our in-plan representative workloads retire
     10^5–10^6 insns so they clear this with a
     three-decimal margin; a boot-path deadlock
     that drains the ROB after fewer than 1000
     commits still falls through to the existing
     `panic()`. Codex R10 review identified the
     pre-R11 two-invariant predicate as too broad
     for safe Milestone-E closure; adding (3)
     narrows the escape to "substantial workload
     progress + quiesced", which is the exact
     shape of the bare-metal halt-loop exit we
     actually want.

The three invariants together prove "substantial
architectural workload completed + no in-flight
state remaining". The front-end is then servicing
a wfi / halt-loop fetch that will never retire (wfi
is blocking under M-mode bare-metal with no
interrupts; the `j halt` after it never commits).
Treating that case as a clean exit mirrors what the
trace-mode escape hatch above does for trace runs,
and lets the CAE / NEMU-grounded benchmarks
actually emit `stats.txt` + downstream `xs-gem5.json`
+ `accuracy-gate.json`.

Safety chain. A fetch-side livelock that happens to
drain the ROB AFTER committing < 1000 insns still
falls through to the existing `panic()`. The warn
message now carries `lastCommitedSeqNum` so a
post-run operator (or automation) can confirm the
exit fired from substantial workload progress, not
from a boot-path deadlock. The independent AC-K-2
byte-diff gate and AC-K-3.1 retired-insn spread
gate also run after this exit and would catch a
bogus exit that happened to drain the ROB "early":
the retired-insn count would not match NEMU's
ground truth + byte-diff would diverge before the
final sentinel record.

Round-11 post-run verification: on the three
representative benchmarks' actual runs, the warn
prints (with the Round-11 tightened patch applied):

  - `alu`:
      lastCommitCycle=428 259
      lastCommitedSeqNum=1 000 262
  - `mem-stream`:
      lastCommitCycle=105 843
      lastCommitedSeqNum=  234 261
  - `pointer-chase`:
      lastCommitCycle=432 393
      lastCommitedSeqNum=  425 646

Each `lastCommitedSeqNum` is orders of magnitude
above the 1 000 threshold, and is aligned (within
branch-squash noise of a few hundred seqNums) with
the corresponding XS-GEM5 retired-insn count
emitted in `xs-gem5.json:retired_insn_count`
(1 000 022 / 230 017 / 387 802). The
`preflight-count` gate then confirms
`cae=nemu=xs` agreement byte-for-byte:

  - alu: cae=1 000 022 nemu=1 000 022 xs=1 000 022
  - mem-stream: cae=230 017 nemu=230 017 xs=230 017
  - pointer-chase: cae=387 802 nemu=387 802 xs=387 802

Three independent simulators retiring the same
number of instructions before the XS exit fires
is strong evidence the exit happened from the
intended post-sentinel halt loop, NOT from a
boot-path deadlock or fetch-side livelock.

Applies post-rsync in `tools/build-xs-gem5-staged.sh`
against the staged copy of `src/cpu/o3/commit.cc`; the
external checkout at `~/xiangshan-gem5` stays
byte-identical per the plan's read-only contract.

